{"key":"processedPost-11579023","value":{"id":11579023,"first":11578916,"last":11579101,"when":1259890778,"utime":"12/04/09 03:39 AM","content":"No to both.&nbsp; I run one of those so-called HEPA units with paper filters in my living room all winter when the wood stove is heating our house.&nbsp; It cuts down about 50% on the wood ash that settles as dust on our furniture and every thing else.&nbsp; However, if it can only collect half of the relatively large dust particles, I wouldn't trust it to stop much of the bacteria and mold spores that will be in the air.&nbsp; In fact it may stir them up.&nbsp; A few years ago, I tried exactly what you're suggesting, by shutting it off before beginning sterile work.&nbsp; My success was higher without ever running it in the first place.<br /><br />If you're serious about the hobby and are going to be in it for awhile, pony up the cash for a laminar flow hood.<br />RR","title":"Re: Contam HELP"}}